snippet.textDisplay: 0:03 - WAY before its invention. Money is just goats or pigs or turnips made lighter and smaller and therefore easier to carry around, without having it spoil after some time. They are just a token meant to prove that you actually do own so and so many goats, pigs or turnips, which you are actually able to provide for confiscation in exchange for whatever favour or resource you're getting from someone else. It could be gold, it could be seashells or whatever, provided it's rare and hard to forge. Why do people still not understand the simple logic behind it, is beyond my comprehension.

snippet.textDisplay: Robin Hood is not a communist or a socialist. He was a liberal hero that believed in helping the little guy when the big guy became corrupt. In the older tales, he didn’t even give money to the poor. He’d capture corrupt priests and officials and force them to perform the tasks that they were always supposed to before setting them on their way. I do have to say, though, I enjoyed the history lesson in some of the different adaptations of the story. Robin Hood is one of my all-time favorite characters, so this was a welcome surprise.

snippet.textDisplay:
Point of Order: Robin Hood isn't an indictment of capitalism per se, because Robin Hood predates capitalism by hundreds of years. Capitalism as we know it is an outgrowth of the Renaissance Italian city-states such as Florence and Venice; Pre-Renaissance the social system in England was not Capitalism but Feudalism. Even Marx and Engels wrote about the distinction, and considered capitalism a necessary transition between feudal states and communist states. Before you can have workers owning the means of production, you need the means of production to be created by capitalists in the first place. That's why, in Afghanistan, some of our better allies were the old Communist party from the Soviet days. They saw a capitalist state as a necessary first step to transition Afghanistan to Communism; you can't go directly to it from feudalism, which state Afghanistan is still in.

For your googling pleasure, I suggest 'Historical materialism', 'Das Kapital', and 'Marx'.

snippet.textDisplay:
Possibly the most ignorant take on Robin Hood is to associate him with communism.

Robin Hood was about holding authority figures responsible; it had absolutely NOTHING to do with free trade, capitalism, redistribution, or even for that matter, RICH OR POOR.

His stories started popping up only a century after the Magna Carta, and are set during the same regime as it, for Pete's sake. It was about ensuring that the nobility maintained their Noblesse Oblige, that they didn't unfairly interfere with their subjects' prosperity (a very capitalist notion), and that they actually met their responsibilities lest they be deposed or harassed by the very kingdom they purport to rule.

Yet you just couldn't help but start your entire video by applying wholly modern notions and sensibilities to a story nearly a millennium old, and by inserting your own insipid hot take on capitalism, which the stories of Robin Hood had nothing to do with in the first place.

It had been a long time since I bothered watching your videos, but I had really looked forward to an entertaining breakdown of my favorite Robin Hood stories. Then you went and ruined it by completely failing to understand the source material.

Disappointing, OSP. Truly disappointing.

snippet.textDisplay:
Fun fact: nowadays in Robin Hood, it's fairly common for Robin to have a saracen character included in his team (not always, I think the Ridley Scott's movie from was it 2010 doesn't have one, but like), but their characterisations vary even more wildly than most others'; Prince of Thieves has the guy follow Robin because Robin saved his life so he feels obligated to follow him until he can somehow pay back that debt, in the BBC tv show it's a woman who starts out disguised as a guy for some reason, whereas the newest (was it 2019 or 2018?) movie adaptation apparently fuses the saracen character with Little John.

You'll also notice, if you look into it, that the saracen character doesn't appear in any old ballads, or novels, or even in the early movie adaptations. The first appearance of a saracen outlaw in Robin Hood is in the 1984-1986 fantasy show Robin of Sherwood (btw I wouldn't be surprised if some of the association of Robin Hood with paganism came from RoS, as that show drew heavily from celtic folklore and overall threw straight-up fantasy elements into the mix, which isn't that common in Robin Hood). He's Nasir, he's an ex-assassin, his backstory is kinda complicated. Originally he wasn't even meant to become a regular character or a good guy, but just a minion to the one-off villain in the show's first story, that Robin would kill near the end. He didn't even have any lines. But the actor was pretty close in age to the outlaws' actors, and they became pretty good friends during filming, (and apparently some of the women of the shooting crew thought that Mark Ryan looked pretty hot, and mentioned this to the writer) so the writer decided to have Robin spare Nasir's life, and have Nasir become one of the outlaws.

So the saracen outlaw is a very new character in Robin Hood. But unlike a lot of the characters one adaptation or another adds to the outlaws, the saracen stuck. He was actually popularised by Robin Hood Prince of Thieves, which... overall has been accused of ripping off of Robin of Sherwood, but since I haven't seen the movie, I don't know if that accusation has any point. Either way, in the case of the saracen outlaw, Prince of Thieves very nearly strayed into the realm of copyright violations. Story goes, the writer and director of the movie had seen Robin of Sherwood back when it had aired, and had liked it, but neither had ever realized Nasir was an original character of the show, not an older part of the lore. It was only when the stunt director of the movie (who had also worked as stunt director and stuntman in RoS) saw the script that anyone noticed the mistake. Which was then corrected by quickly changing the character's name from Nasir to whatever they actually used for him in the final movie.

After Prince of Thieves, the saracen character stuck around, but due to it being such a new addition, its name and backstory vary a lot (and apparently even gender isn't fixed, judging by the BBC adaptation).


Also btw, I'm pretty sure Robin of Sherwood was also one of the earliest, if not the earliest, adapation where King Richard was portrayed as sucking just as bad as his brother. (He also appeared in like exactly one episode, and then went off to Normandy to fight another war, and in one episode next season it was mentioned he'd died there offscreen, making John, who continued appearing throughout the rest of the show, the king.)
